WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.320
I'm Beatriz, I came all the way from Brazil to talk to you about how to make awesome automations

00:00:12.320 --> 00:00:14.840
with GitHub Actions.

00:00:14.840 --> 00:00:21.680
So anyone here has to run scripts like every day, every week, every month.

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:28.760
If you do that, GitHub Actions probably will be useful to you.

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:34.720
So I'm here to talk about what is GitHub Actions and how can we run our scripts with it.

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:47.240
So GitHub Actions has been heavily used by our package developers and for running checks

00:00:47.240 --> 00:00:53.279
on packages, building the package website and documentation, and if you are a package

00:00:53.279 --> 00:00:55.599
developer, you can easily do that.

00:00:55.599 --> 00:01:00.880
Using package, use this, which is my favorite package, and you can also see a lot of other

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:06.559
examples in this awesome RLib Actions repository.

00:01:06.559 --> 00:01:10.599
So how important is GitHub Actions to RStudio?

00:01:10.599 --> 00:01:12.279
And Posit.

00:01:12.279 --> 00:01:21.959
So I look up in the GitHub Action API, no, GitHub API to get the action run, and we can

00:01:21.959 --> 00:01:30.080
see that in two years, the runs, completed runs for these organizations, which stores

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:34.019
our favorite packages, increase it more than four times.

00:01:34.019 --> 00:01:41.839
So GitHub Actions is really important for RStudio and Posit to run checks on our packages

00:01:41.839 --> 00:01:45.720
and build the documentation and stuff.

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:51.720
But I told you about what package developers can do, but most people that I know are not

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:53.959
package developers.

00:01:53.959 --> 00:02:00.120
So I'm here to talk about, you guys, how you can use that as well.

00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:05.320
I've been using it in two years, and in the beginning, it was a bit hard for me, so I'm

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:10.199
trying to facilitate this process, right?

00:02:10.199 --> 00:02:15.520
So we can run arbitrary R scripts, like scrape data from the internet.

00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:19.000
I do that a lot, but the government data.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.800
When reports with R markdown in Quarto, we can send emails and save results, all doing

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:32.399
GitHub Actions with R. So this is a simple example of a workflow file, but I don't expect

00:02:32.399 --> 00:02:40.880
you to understand this right now, but the point is, this first part, we have the events,

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:46.919
and this part tells when the workflow should run.

00:02:46.919 --> 00:02:52.399
In this case, we have a button to press, so when we press a button, we start the workflow,

00:02:52.399 --> 00:02:54.000
and also we have a schedule.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.479
So I'm telling the computer that it has to be run every day.

00:02:58.479 --> 00:03:03.479
The second part is the name of the workflow, and the third part is what the workflow should

00:03:03.479 --> 00:03:04.479
do.

00:03:04.479 --> 00:03:11.679
So this part, the jobs part, imagine that it's a virtual machine that belongs to GitHub,

00:03:11.679 --> 00:03:17.399
there's nothing installed, and you have to tell what should be installed in order to

00:03:17.399 --> 00:03:19.960
run R script and what should be done.

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:25.880
So I'm telling that I want to run a Ubuntu machine, you can also use Windows machine

00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:33.600
and Apple machines, macOS machines, and I'm installing R, but this is super easy because

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:41.199
of the Rlib action repository, there is a setup there that we just use it, and then

00:03:41.199 --> 00:03:49.000
I'm saying that I want to run my awesome R script in the end, and remember, that part,

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:54.839
you have to install all the packages there, otherwise it won't work, it will break.

00:03:54.839 --> 00:04:01.759
So this is a really quick presentation, and I prepared more examples in my blog, and I

00:04:01.759 --> 00:04:06.839
hope I will continue to do that, so you can see more examples there.

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:12.199
I would like to thank especially RStudio for the diversity scholarship, otherwise I couldn't

00:04:12.199 --> 00:04:19.440
be here, our ladies, the creators and contributors of Rlib actions and articulation, and you

00:04:19.440 --> 00:04:23.440
can find me on Twitter, and my blog is BeaMills.com.

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:24.440
Thank you.

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:24.440


